	<MaterialsList materials={[{"name":"Drawing paper or canvas","isOptional":false},{"name":"Pencils, charcoal, colored pencils, markers, pens, oil pastels, etc.","isOptional":false},{"name":"Paints","isOptional":false},{"name":"Collage materials","description":"magazines, newspapers, fabric scraps, recycled materials, found objects.","isOptional":false},{"name":"Scissors","isOptional":false},{"name":"Glue","isOptional":false},{"name":"Whiteboard or large chart paper","isOptional":false},{"name":"Markers","isOptional":false},{"name":"Notebooks or paper","isOptional":false},{"name":"Pens/Pencils","isOptional":false}]} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"ART"} content={"<strong>Visualizing Urgency: Climate Action Through Pop Art</strong>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"(30-60 MINUTES)"} content={"<strong>Introduction</strong><br>Begin with a dynamic introduction to Pop Art. Explain its origins in the 1950s and 1960s, its reaction to consumer culture, and its use of mass media imagery.<br>Pop Art emerged as a significant art movement in both the United Kingdom and the United States during the 50s and 60s. It was a reaction to several things:\n<ul>\n<li><em>Rebellion against Abstract Expressionism:</em> In the post-WWII era, Abstract Expressionism was a dominant force in the art world. Artists like Jackson Pollock and Willem de Kooning emphasized subjective expression and non-representational forms. Pop Art, in contrast, rejected this focus on individual emotion and embraced more accessible, representational imagery.</li>\n<li><em>The rise of consumer culture:</em> The post-war period also witnessed a surge in consumerism. Mass production, advertising, and the availability of new consumer goods transformed everyday life. Pop Art directly engaged with this phenomenon, drawing inspiration from and often critiquing the culture of consumption.</li>\n<li><em>Influence of mass media:</em> Pop Art artists were fascinated by the power and ubiquity of mass media. They incorporated imagery from:</li>\n<li><em>Advertising:</em> Product packaging, billboards, and commercials became sources of artistic inspiration.</li>\n<li><em>Comic Books:</em> Their bold graphics and narrative style were adopted and transformed.</li>\n<li><em>Television and Film:</em> Celebrities and iconic scenes from popular culture appeared in Pop Art.</li>\n<li><em>Photography:</em> Mass-produced photographs and news images were recontextualized as art.</li>\n<li><em>Blurring the lines between high and low art:</em> Traditionally, there was a clear distinction between “high art” (fine art, classical art) and “low art” (popular culture, commercial art). Pop Art deliberately blurred these boundaries, elevating everyday objects and mass-produced imagery to the status of art.</li>\n<li><em>Social commentary (often subversive):</em> While Pop Art celebrated some aspects of popular culture, it also often contained a critical edge. Artists used irony and satire to comment on:</li>\n<li><em>Consumerism’s superficiality:</em> Questioning the pursuit of material goods.</li>\n<li><em>The power of advertising:</em> Exposing its manipulative techniques.</li>\n<li><em>The cult of celebrity:</em> Examining the role of fame in society.</li>\n</ul><br>In essence, Pop Art reflected and challenged the changing social, cultural, and economic landscape of the mid-20th century. It was a bold and innovative movement that continues to influence art and visual culture today.<br>Highlight key characteristics:\n<ul>\n<li>Bold colors and graphic style.</li>\n<li>Use of everyday objects and popular culture references.</li>\n<li>Repetition and serial imagery.</li>\n<li>Irony and satire.</li>\n</ul><br>Showcase examples of iconic Pop Art, focusing on:\n<ul>\n<li>Different techniques (painting, printmaking, collage).</li>\n<li>The power of visual communication and social commentary.</li>\n</ul><br>`\t`<em>Examples:</em>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.wikiart.org/en/andy-warhol\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Works of Andy Warhol</a> His iconic screen prints and photographs of celebrities and consumer goods (e.g., “Campbell’s Soup Cans,” “Marilyn Monroe”) showcase the repetition and mass production of consumer culture.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.wikiart.org/en/roy-lichtenstein/all-works#!#filterName:all-paintings-chronologically,resultType:masonry\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Works of Roy Lichtenstein</a> His comic-book inspired paintings with bold outlines and Ben-Day dots (e.g., “Whaam!,” “Drowning Girl”) demonstrate the use of graphic style and context.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.wikiart.org/en/james-rosenquist\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Works of James Rosenquist</a> His large-scale collages that juxtapose images from advertising and popular culture (e.g., “F-111”) explore themes of consumerism and technology.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.wikiart.org/en/claes-oldenburg\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Works of Claes Oldenburg</a> His sculptures of everyday objects (e.g., “Giant Hamburger,” “Soft Toilet”) transform the ordinary into the extraordinary, challenging our perceptions of reality.</li>\n</ul><br>Facilitate a brief discussion.\n<ul>\n<li>What are your initial reactions to Pop Art?</li>\n<li>How does it differ from traditional art styles?</li>\n<li>How can Pop Art be used to address social and political issues?</li>\n</ul><br>Introduce and/or reintroduce UN Global Goal 13: Take urgent action to combat climate change and its impacts. Emphasize the urgency of the climate crisis and the need for immediate action. Briefly review key targets and indicators if wanted.<br>Engage students in a though-provoking discussion about how Pop Art can be used to explore themes of climate change. Pose questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>How can Pop Art’s bold visual style capture the urgency of the climate crisis?</li>\n<li>Can Pop Art’s use of mass media imagery help us critique consumerism and its impact on the environment?</li>\n<li>How can Pop Art’s techniques (repetition, bright colors) be used to visualize climate data or solutions?</li>\n<li>Can Pop Art’s ironic or satirical approach be used to challenge climate change denial or inaction?</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Exploring Pop Art Techniques and Brainstorming"} content={"<p>Demonstrate and discuss key Pop Art techniques that students can incorporate into their artwork:\n<ul>\n<li><em>Bold Colors and Graphic Style:</em> Use saturated colors, clear lines, and simplified shapes.</li>\n<li><em>Repetition and Serial Imagery:</em> Repeat images or patterns to emphasize a message or create a visual rhythm.</li>\n<li><em>Everday objects and popular culture references:</em> Incorporate images of consumer goods, technology, or celebrities.</li>\n<li><em>Text and typography:</em> Use words and phrases in a bold and graphic way.</li>\n<li><em>Collage and mixed media:</em> Combine different materials and images to create a layered effect.</li>\n</ul><br>Each student brainstorms ideas for a Pop Art piece that addresses a specific aspect of Global Goal 13. Encourage students to:\n<ul>\n<li>Choose a specific climate change issue or solution to focus on.</li>\n<li>Use Pop Art techniques to create a visually striking and impactful message.</li>\n<li>Consider the emotional response they want to evoke in the viewer.</li>\n<li>Connect their artwork to their own experiences and observations.</li>\n</ul><br>Examples of Pop Art concepts for each target:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Target 13.1</strong> <em>(Strengthen resilience and adaptive capacity)</em></li>\n<li>A series of repeated images showing a city skyline before, during, and after a climate-related disaster (e.g., flood, hurricane)</li>\n<li>A portrait of a community working together to rebuild after a disaster, using bold colors and graphic style to convey strength and resilience.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 13.2</strong> <em>(Integrate climate change measures)</em></li>\n<li>A collage juxtaposing images of polluting industries with images of renewable energy sources, highlighting the need for a transition.</li>\n<li>A graphic representation of greenhouse gas emissions data, using bold colors and repetition to visualize the scale of the problem.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 13.3</strong> <em>(Improve education and awareness)</em></li>\n<li>A series of Pop Art posters with bold text and imagery, promoting climate action and sustainable practices.</li>\n<li>A portrait of a young activist speaking out for climate justice, using bright colors and dynamic composition to convey passion and urgency.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 13.a</strong> <em>(Mobilize finance)</em></li>\n<li>An image of money flowing from developed countries to developing countries, with a focus on equity and justice.</li>\n<li>A satirical take on the financial costs of climate inaction, using ironic imagery and text.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 13.b</strong> <em>(Promote mechanisms for capacity-building)</em></li>\n<li>A collage showing people from different backgrounds learning about climate change and developing solutions.</li>\n<li>A portrait of a woman leader advocating for climate action in her community, using bold colors and graphic style to convey empowerment.</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Artwork Creation"} content={"<p>Students create their Pop Art pieces using the chosen medium and techniques.  Encourage students to:\n<ul>\n<li>Experiment with color, composition, and scale.</li>\n<li>Use text and imagery effectively.</li>\n<li>Embrace the bold and graphic style of Pop Art.</li>\n<li>Express their creativity and personal interpretations.</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Presentation and Discussion"} content={"<p>If time allows, students can present their completed artworks to the class.<br>Facilitate a discussion after each presentation, asking questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>What is the main message of the artwork?</li>\n<li>How did the artist use Pop Art techniques to convey their message?</li>\n<li>How does the artwork relate to Global Goal 13 and its targets?</li>\n<li>What impact do you think the artwork could have on viewers?</li>\n<li>What did you learn about climate change and its connection to art?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Reflection and Summary"} content={"<p>Have students reflect on their learning experience through discussion or writing.<br>Ask guiding questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>How did the bold colors, graphic style, and repetition (key elements of Pop Art) help you communicate the urgency or the scale of climate change issues in your artwork?</li>\n<li>What did you learn about the power of popular imagery and everyday objects in art to make a serious message about climate action more accessible or impactful?</li>\n<li>Did creating a Pop Art piece about climate change allow you to express emotions or ideas (like hope, frustration, or determination) in a unique way?</li>\n<li>How did the process of transforming ideas about climate into a visually striking piece change your perception of art’s role in activism?</li>\n<li>What did you discover about your own creative voice when using Pop Art techniques to address a global issue?</li>\n<li>What new insights did you gain about Global Goal 13 and the importance of urgent action to combat climate change through this artistic exploration?</li>\n<li>Hoe did the diverse Pop Art pieces created by your classmates highlight the many different facets of climate action (e.g., resilience, policy, education, finance)?</li>\n<li>Did any specific artwork or the process of creating it make you think differently about a climate challenge or solution in your own community or globally?</li>\n<li>What common themes or powerful messages about climate change emerged across the different artworks you saw?</li>\n<li>How does a Pop Art approach help us to visualize climate data or complex solutions in a more engaging way?</li>\n<li>Did creating your Pop Art piece spark any personal connections or reflections on your own impact on the environment or the climate crisis?</li>\n<li>What emotions did you connect with while creating your artwork, and how might those emotions motivate you to take action related to Global Goal 13?</li>\n<li>What is one key takeaway about climate action and the power of creative expression that you will remember from this lesson?</li>\n<li>How has this lesson influenced your thinking about your own role in advocating for climate action in your daily life or community?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Assessment"} content={"<ul>\n<li>Consistent and enthusiastic involvement in all phases of the lesson, including the introduction to Pop Art, technique explorations, individual art creation, and class discussions.</li>\n<li>Comprehension of Global Goal 13, targets and core concepts. This will be evidenced through the symbolism and intention within Pop Art piece(s) and verbal explanations during sharing and discussion.</li>\n<li>Originality and effectiveness in applying chosen Pop Art elements (e.g., bold colors, graphic style, repetition, popular culture references, text/typography, collage) to convey their message about climate action.</li>\n<li>How clearly and powerfully the finished artwork communicates its intended message about Global Goal 13. Did the artwork successfully evoke thought or emotion related to teh goal, or effectively highlight a climate challenge/solution?</li>\n<li>Willingness to experiment with the materials and techniques, embracing the unique qualities of Pop Art, and demonstrating problem-solving during the creative process.</li>\n<li>Ability to articulate artistic choices and to interpret and provide thoughtful feedback on classmates’ artwork, connecting it to Global Goal 13.</li>\n<li>Nuance and depth of understanding demonstrated in reflections, particularly concerning the role of art in social change and the complexities of climate action.</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

</div>
